ing them. And the king examined the two chamberlains, and they confessed, and were <RF><i>Lit.</i> led away, see Acts 12:19.<Rf>executed. And the king wrote these things for a memorial: also Mardochæus wrote concerning these matters. And the king commanded Mardochæus to attend in the palace, and gave gifts for this service. And Aman the son of Amadathes the Bugean was honourable in the sight of the king, and he endeavored to hurt Mardochæus and his people, because of the two chamberlains of the king.]<CM><RF><i>Note.—</i> In the <i>Heb.</i> and some copies of LXX., Esther begins here.<Rf>And it came to pass after these <RF><i>Gr.</i> words.<Rf>things in the days of Artaxerxes, —(this Artaxerxes ruled over a hundred and twenty-seven provinces from India)—
